        <h1>LeetCode 3651: Number of Subsequences with Even Sum (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                Given an array nums of positive integers, return the number of non-empty subsequences with an even sum. Since the answer may be large, return it modulo 10<sup>9</sup> + 7. A subsequence is a sequence that can be derived from the array by deleting some or no elements without changing the order of the remaining elements.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: nums = [1,2,3]<br/>
                Output: 4<br/>
                Explanation: The subsequences with even sum are: [2], [1,3], [2,3], [1,2,3]. Note that [1,2] has odd sum 3 and is not counted.<br/><br/>
                Input: nums = [2,4,6]<br/>
                Output: 7<br/>
                Explanation: All non-empty subsequences except [] have even sum: [2], [4], [6], [2,4], [2,6], [4,6], [2,4,6].<br/><br/>
                Input: nums = [1,1,1,1]<br/>
                Output: 6<br/>
                Explanation: Subsequences with even sum are those with an even number of elements: [1,1] appears 6 times.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int subsequenceCount(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums) {
        const int MOD = 1e9 + 7;
        int n = nums.size();
        
        // Count even and odd numbers
        int evenCount = 0, oddCount = 0;
        for (int num : nums) {
            if (num % 2 == 0) {
                evenCount++;
            } else {
                oddCount++;
            }
        }
        
        // For each even number, we can either include it or not: 2^evenCount choices
        // For odd numbers, we need even count of them
        // Total subsequences with even sum:
        // If oddCount == 0: 2^evenCount - 1 (exclude empty subsequence)
        // If oddCount &gt; 0: 2^evenCount * 2^(oddCount-1) - 1
        
        long long result = 1;
        
        // Calculate 2^evenCount
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; evenCount; i++) {
            result = (result * 2) % MOD;
        }
        
        if (oddCount &gt; 0) {
            // Calculate 2^(oddCount-1)
            long long oddPower = 1;
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; oddCount - 1; i++) {
                oddPower = (oddPower * 2) % MOD;
            }
            result = (result * oddPower) % MOD;
        }
        
        // Subtract 1 for empty subsequence
        result = (result - 1 + MOD) % MOD;
        
        return result;
    }
};</code></pre>
